<h2>Project Idea</h2>
<br><br><br><br>

<h3>Overview</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>
        <h4>Topic</h4>
        <p>Telkom+ purpose is to create a connectivity towards “non-smart” devices that aren’t able to connect directly to the internet and help organise the wide variety of smart devices that are currently available. With the ever-growing market of smart technology, household appliances today are becoming more and more feature rich and their capabilities are higher than previous non internet capable versions of themselves. We want our users to have the complete freedom to control and connect devices for a better lifestyle, giving them no restraint to which device can or can’t connect to our application, but rather encouraging them to connect “non-smart” devices. The ability to streamline them all within a simple, user friendly interface is what our main goals are.</p>
        <p>The expected outcome is to support the growth of smart technology. With the developments of required technology, such as sensors and faster internet, becoming cheaper and more accessible, more people are incorporating smart appliances into their daily lives. As more people become more accustomed to things being on demand and ready when they need it, the demand for smart technology rises and the need to be able to control them.</p>
        </li>
        <br>
        <li>
        <h4>Motivation</h4>
        <p>Our motivation behind this project is the growth of IoT. In 2018, a survey was conducted by the Statista Research Department which produced an estimate of 22 Billion IoT devices connected around the world. In the future the amount of IoT devices that were predicted by Statista will be 38.6 Billion IoT devices by the end of 2025. Due to this growth, it would be necessary and helpful if all devices could be connected and controlled via a single application on the phone to allow for easier and more efficient use. What makes this project so interesting is that our product also allows non-smart devices to be controlled via the application.</p>
        <p></p>
        </li>
        <br>
        <li>
        <h4>Landscape</h4>
        <p></p>
        </li>
    </ul>

<br><br><br>

<h3>Detailed Description</h3>
<h4>Aims</h4>
<p></p>
<br><br>

<h4>Plans and Progress</h4>
<h5>Telkom+ Product (Power Strip)</h5>
<p>Telkom+ is a ‘smart’ power strip that connects all electrical appliances to an app where they can be controlled. This product of Telkom+ will connect all devices that are plugged into the strip and act as a way to either control all features of any smart device connected to the power strip and/or have the ability to turn off or on any devices via the app. What inspired us to do such a project was because of situations where a light was left on outside of your room and it needed to be turned off, however, you are already tucked inside of your bed and do not have the energy to leave it. Other situations that also inspired us would be whether you left your mini electrical stove on or off and are already on a plane heading straight to the Netherlands. It is situations like these that made us want to come up with a project idea such as this.
Originally, Telkom+ was just a simple minicomputer that uses Raspberry Pi as the "Middleman" for the wall power socket to the electrical appliance to make it automated. The product itself would then be connected to the home Wi-Fi to obtain the static IP address of the Raspberry Pi and so the Wi-Fi signal can control the Raspberry Pi to kill the power or reconnect the power to the electrical appliance. Having reconsidered the project itself, it was decided that the original idea would be too hard to implement/create realistically as it was very confusing to understand all the technicalities behind it. Instead, we had come up with the idea to make it into a ‘smart’ power strip which would have the ability to turn on and off devices, control all features of any smart device, and have a similar interactive AI feature that devices such as Alexa, and Google Home have. The reason behind including an interactive AI system in the product was because since our product was able to control any device using an app, to make it easier for users, an interactive AI would be suitable for this situation as it would allow for much more efficient use.  Although it can be argued whether our product needs an app as another way to control the devices, it is still necessary for users who have any trouble speaking or are not within range for the product to register their voice. The interactive AI feature also puts our product into the smart home device category, so companies such as Amazon and Google would be some of our main competitors. What differentiates our product with any of these companies existing smart devices, however, is that our product can utilise any device which needs power, meaning that devices which don’t have any smart features such as a microwave can still be used with our product as long as it has a power cable to connect it to it.</p>
<h5>Telkom+ Product (Power Strip)</h5>
<p>Alongside the actual product itself, there will be a phone application that would be compatible with all phone OS, whether it is iOS or Android. This application would allow users to control all their devices connected to a power strip. If there are any smart devices plugged into the power strip, users would be able to unlock all controls/features that the smart device has. For example, changing the colour of light on a smart led. If there are any non-smart devices plugged into the power strip, such as a microwave, users would be given the ability to turn on or off the device. In a report created by the Natural Resource Defense Council (NRDC), they talk about how they have found that many of today's smart TVs use a lot more power in standby mode if they're waiting for a voice assistant to turn them on which in some cases is enough to double their annual energy consumption. Due to this report, we as a group decided that by including a feature where users are able to turn off or on any device connected/plugged into the power strip without it having to be on standby mode, they are able to also save energy, reducing the cost of their electricity bill.
When using the app, assuming the user has already created an account, first, a username and password are requested or, if enabled, users can use the FaceID recognition that iOS has or the user fingerprint. After the credentials are verified by the app, users will be taken to the home. The home screen consists of 3 main features, settings, devices, and a voice command button for the AI feature. Within the ‘settings’ menu users are given options such as adjusting the information for their profile and a help and forum menu where they will be able to find help for any issues that they encounter. For the ‘devices’ menu users are able to see all of their electrical devices that have been connected to a power strip. For all devices, if clicked on, users are given the ability to turn it on or off. There will also be an indication for the user which shows whether the device is turned off or on to help prevent any mistakes if the user wants to turn off a device but accidentally turns it on. For smart devices, if clicked on, users are given all the functions/features that the smart device can do, able to control it. If a new device is connected to the power strip, it will automatically be synced and listed inside of the users’ ‘devices’ menu. If a device is removed from the power strip, the device will no longer be able to be controlled via the app, until plugged/connected again to the power strip. Users’ are also able to redesign the interface of the app in the ‘devices’ menu as they are able to move each device on this list into a different location (i.e. moving a device from the bottom of the list to the top). This would help users’ access some of their devices quicker than others as the user might prioritize or use a device more than others and want/need to access it quicker. Lastly, within the ‘voice command’ feature, users’ are able to interact with the AI. By including this feature in the app, users are able to access information without having to leave the app and use a browser. As other smart devices have this feature in their applications, it is only fitting if our application utilises it too so that no consumer would feel ripped off by not including a feature that a competitor has.</p>
<br><br>

<h4>Roles</h4>
<p></p>
<br><br>

<h4>Scope and Limits</h4>
<p>The scope of this project involves the ability to interlink communication of tasks towards multiple internet connectable household appliances, smart devices, and be able organize them and operate them all from the convenience of an application on your internet capable mobile device. This is the major priority of Telkom+ and our focus, while we are focusing on that primarily. Our secondary opportunity to provide additional benefits compared to our competitors is the implementation of an application controlled power strip that allows control of which devices are connected and be able to turn them on or off allowing for a remote on/off switch on applications that can be used to save power, and turn on a certain device the same time another is being utilized. While this is another deliverable that Telkom+ aims to achieve, this is not our main priority as we believe that the successful implantation of the main application to be developed is the main selling point to our idea.</p>
<br><br>

<h4>Tools and Technologies</h4>
<p>Our base software used to create this is Raspberry Pi, we would need this to create the device that connects the “non-smart” devices together. We would also need the licences for current programming software’s for Android such as, Java, Kotlin, C# or C++ just to name a few and software’s for Apple like, Swift. We would need hardware to create the adaptor for “non-smart” devices and the Raspberry Pi. Our group has experience programming in Java, C and some Micro bit experience, but the skills in these categories are still basic. None of us have any experience with Swift, Kotlin or Raspberry Pi, and this project gives us a chance to learn and pick up a few things for these languages and hardware.</p>
<br><br>

